<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN'S CONSUMER CONFIDENCE HITS LOWEST LEVEL SINCE DEC. 2001
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei, May 29 (CNA) 05/29/07  16:47:51 (By Y.F. Low)
</P>
<P>
Taiwan's consumer confidence index (CCI) for May dropped to its
lowest level since December 2001, indicating that consumers are
becoming conservative about making purchases owing to their
decreased faith in the economy, according to the results of a
survey released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The survey, publicized by National Central University's Research
Center for Taiwan Economic Development, shows that the CCI for
May stood at 65.52, down 2.15 points from the previous month.
</P>
<P>
Five out of the six indicators used in the survey declined in
May, with the "next six months' domestic consumer price"
indicator registering the greatest decrease, dropping 6.85 points
from April to stand at 32.60, the lowest level since 2001.
</P>
<P>
Coming in second was the "next six months' domestic economic
outlook" indicator, which slid 5.95 points from April to 45.85.
</P>
<P>
The "next six months' employment opportunities" indicator dropped
2.65 points to 72.25, while the "next six months' family
financial status" indicator fell 2.35 points to 51.50, also the
lowest level since 2001.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the "timing for buying durable goods over the next six
months" indicator dipped 0.35 points to 112.50.
</P>
<P>
The only indicator that rose in May was the "timing for investing
in the stock market over the next six months, " which increased
5.20 points from April to 78.40.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted via telephone from May 19-21 among 2,327
adults around Taiwan, has a margin of error of two percentage
points.
</P>
